passages.text: August 29, 2025 04:18 AM GMT
2025 Target: Current run rate looks on track to achieve its full year target and the company reiterated its \(9\%\) core NPM target.
2Q25: Top-line achieved positive growth helped by diversified product portfolio. Margin expansion continued on lower raw milk price and savings in opex.
2H25: Yili expects its liquid milk to outperform markets while demand remains weak. Other businesses are expected to maintain good momentum.
Raw milk: Yili noted lower impairment and better S- D dynamics across the industry ahead of festival peak season. Momentum post festivals is key watch point.
Capital allocation: Management reiterated dividend payout at no less than \(70\%\) with total dividend amount likely no less than 2024 level.

Liquid milk: Yili noted no significant demand pick up in July and Aug. Management saw stabilized liquid milk market share in 1H25 and strong growth in fresh milk at \(>20\%\) yoy. It is confident of gaining market share as the industry improves. IMF business: The company saw mild growth in IMF market in 1H25 and expects single- digit growth for 2025. It highlighted that Yili's IMF business achieved No.1 in market share in 1H25 (cow and goat milk formula combined). Online channel was a bright spot in 1H25 with \(>30\%\) sales growth. Maternity subsidies are still at an initial stage and Yili expects top- line contribution starting in 2H25.

Ice cream: Market share in China remained solid with overseas sales up strongly in 1H25 by \(14\%\) yoy. Cheese and other dairy products: 2B business achieved more than \(20\%\) growth in 1H25 and 2C business also recorded positive growth in 1H25.
Competition with Freshly- Made Drinks (FMD): Yili saw competition from FMD putting pressure on packaged liquid milk but the impact should not persist.
Channel: Emerging channel (i.e. Sam's Club, discount stores, etc) accounted for more than \(30\%\) sales in liquid milk in 1H25.

- Faster-than-expected demand recovery.- Better margin expansion from more rational investment in marketing and promotion as raw milk oversupply reduces.
- Slower dairy demand growth.- Raw milk oversupply lasts longer than expected, causing continued investment in promotion.
